'''Géza Kresz de Szemlőhegy''' (30 August 1846–10 April 1901)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mek.niif.hu/00300/00355/html/ABC07165/08815.htm|title=Géza Kresz Biography|publisher=Hungarian Electronic Library|work=Magyar Életrajzi Lexikon (Hungarian Biographical Encyclopedia)|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref> was a [[Hungarian people|Hungarian]] physician, founder of the Budapest Voluntary Ambulance Society and the [[Budapesti Korcsolyázó Egylet|Pest Skating Club]].

==Early life==
Kresz was born in [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] to Carl Kresz, a son of a fruiterer from [[Merseburg]], who fled to Hungary to avoid impressment,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kfki.hu/physics/historia/k/r/kresz/kreszpant.html|title=Géza Kresz Biography|publisher=Hungarian Academy of Sciences – KFKI Research Campus|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref> and a daughter of a bookseller. He was the youngest of the six children of the couple.<ref name=ekor>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekor-lap.hu/kultura/2011/165-eve-szuletett-dr-kresz-geza|title=165 éve született Dr. Kresz Géza|publisher=ekor-lap.hu|date=15 August 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref> He studied for physician and earned his medical degree in 1871 in the [[University of Pest]].<ref name=huszadikszazad>{{cite web|url=http://huszadikszazad.hu/sport/meghalt-szemlohegyi-kresz-geza-a-korcsolyazas-elkotelezett-hive|title=Meghalt Szemlőhegyi Kresz Géza a korcsolyázás elkötelezett híve|publisher=huszadikszazad.hu|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref>

==Work==
Kresz first worked as a general practitioner and later became a health officer in the 5th district of Budapest. In 1876 the law for organization of ambulance institutions was enacted, by that it became the responsibility of the police, thus the central district police stations were operating as the first ambulance stations. However, this system could not cope with the increasing number of tasks in the period of indrustialization, and to be able to carry out the rescue missions, Géza Kresz founded the Budapest Voluntary Ambulance Society (Budapesti Önkéntes Mentő Egyesület, BÖME) in 1887, utilizing the model that was used in [[Vienna]] since a few years.<ref name=ekor />

In the coming years he established the organized ambulance system, actively participated in the elimination of cholera and organized the supply of Budapest with breast milk.<ref name=egeszsegkalauz>{{cite web|url=http://www.egeszsegkalauz.hu/egeszsegtar/tisztelet-a-mentoknek-kresz-geza-emlekezete-108778.html|title=Tisztelet a mentőknek! (Kresz Géza emlékezete)|publisher=egeszsegkalauz.hu|work=Hungarian Press Agency|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref> In 1890 the Ambulance Palace (Mentőpalota) was erected on the proposal of Kresz. This was one of the first buildings in Europe that was built as an ambulance station and it still serves as the headquarters of the National Ambulance. The building process took one and a half year and was financed by the donations wealthy citizens. In the yard were found the stables with hayloft and the horse-drawn ambulance coaches. Kresz also had his residence in the Ambulance Palace, where he lived with his family in the second floor.<ref name=ekor />

The second wing of the building was handed over in the second part of the 1890s. The bedrooms of the residential employees, the storage rooms and the Ambulance Museum was placed here. Kresz collected and systematized the instruments and other memorabilia to create this special museum, which is still unique in Europe.<ref name=ekor />

As a devoted fan of ice skating, Kresz played pioneer role in popularizing the sport in Hungary. On his initiation was founded the [[Budapesti Korcsolyázó Egylet|Pest Skating Club]] (Pesti Korcsolyázó Egylet) in 1869 and he set up the first [[Városligeti Műjégpálya|skating rink]] on the frozen lake of the [[City Park (Budapest)|City Park]].<ref name=epulettar>{{cite web|url=http://www.epulettar.hu/projekt/24989.aspx|title=Városligeti Műjégpálya, Budapest XIV.|publisher=Épülettár|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref> Ice skating quickly became a beloved sport, which is shown that the number of skating club members grew from 35 to 432 in the first year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.varosliget.info/mujegpalya.html|title=Műjégpálya|publisher=varosliget.info|accessdate=17 December 2011|language=Hungarian}}</ref>

==Later life and legacy==
[[File:Kresz Géza sírja 2011.jpg|thumb|right|Kresz's Grave at the [[Kerepesi Cemetery]] ]]
In the 1900s a series of ambulance stations were created in Hungarian cities and villages, for them the example to follow was the Budapest Voluntary Ambulance Society.<ref name=ekor /> For his merits he was ennobled by [[Franz Joseph]] on 24 December 1900 and was given the name de Szemlőhegy (Szemlőhegyi).<ref name=huszadikszazad /> In his crest is seen a lion that holds the coat of arms of the National Ambulance, while on the shield are three oak leafs, symbolizing his sons, and three lilies, symbolizing his daughters.<ref name=egeszsegkalauz /> He died on 10 April 1901 and was buried in the [[Kerepesi Cemetery|National Graveyard]] in Budapest. The Ambulance Museum has been renamed in the honour of Kresz, a street in Budapest bears his name and a plaque remembers him by the Ambulance Palace.

